----------------------------------------------------------------------
-- Whole-model verification summary
----------------------------------------------------------------------

-- Summary 1: Added BloodUnit sig extending Resource to represent blood units with a collectionDate field.
-- Summary 2: Removed fact inv_state_must_change which forced every operation to change state, conflicting with test case TC-INV-MAN-02 (no expired units, no change).
-- Summary 3: Updated all predicates and assertions that referenced Blood_Unit_Database as a target to instead reference BloodUnit resources.
-- Summary 4: Relaxed well-formed assertion REQ_INV_MAN_01_well_formed to not require state change (pre != post removed).
-- Summary 5: Adjusted edge case assertions to use BloodUnit and consistent logic.
-- Summary 6: Cleaned up obsolete dedup comment and renamed references to inv_state_must_change_2 (now removed).
-- Assumption 1: Collection dates are abstracted using Int; negative values represent indefinite shelf life.
-- Assumption 2: All blood units are modeled as BloodUnit resources with an owner and accessible actors.
-- Assumption 3: Post-state Post1 corresponds to marking a blood unit as expired; Post2 corresponds to removal from inventory.
-- Assumption 4: Only Inventory_Manager can perform state-changing operations (ec_safe_1).
-- Assumption 5: Admin permission is required for removal (Post2) per ps_reach_Post2; this is a design choice not specified in requirements.
-- Open issue 1: The nfr_fact_avail_redundancy requires at least 2 channels per operation while nfr_fact_perf_channel_limit limits to at most 2, forcing exactly 2 channels?may be too restrictive for all scenarios.
-- Open issue 2: The stronger permission function is defined but never used; can be removed but kept for future use.
-- Open issue 3: Scheduling_API interface is defined but never used in any operation constraint; possibly intended for future scheduling interactions.
-- Open issue 4: The model does not explicitly represent 'available inventory' as a separate concept; removal is modeled only via state change Post2.


